sql:
SELECT ms.flow_id, ms.total_octets, tf.flow_label, tf.flow_key
FROM metrics_summary ms
JOIN traffic_flows tf ON ms.flow_id = tf.flow_id;

SELECT unit_name AS name FROM data_units WHERE unit_type = 'Byte'
UNION ALL
SELECT user_name AS name FROM users WHERE role_id = 1;

SELECT application_name
FROM traffic_flows
WHERE flow_id = 0;

SELECT tf.flow_id, tf.flow_label
FROM traffic_flows tf
WHERE tf.forward_metrics_octets >= tf.reverse_metrics_octets;

SELECT DISTINCT u.user_name 
FROM users u
INNER JOIN data_requests dr ON u.user_id = dr.user_id;

SELECT AVG(forward_metrics_duration) AS average_forward_duration
FROM traffic_flows
WHERE forward_metrics_duration > (SELECT AVG(forward_metrics_duration) FROM traffic_flows);

SELECT request_details
FROM data_requests
WHERE flow_id = 1;

external_knowledge:
- In this metaphorical context, users are referred to as "travelers" and each request is an "flight".;
- "Frequent travelers" refers to users who have made more than 10 requests within the last month. This suggests an active user base, with a significant number of interactions.;
- The "flights typically taken on average" refers to the average response time, not the duration of actual flights. This is a measure of how quickly the service responds to user requests.;
- "Seasoned flyers" are those who have the highest number of requests, indicating they have been using the service more frequently. This metaphor implies experience and regularity in use.

